        <title>Export Untracked, modified, moved and deleted files from a Git repository to archive</title>
        <link>https://manios.org/2014/04/12/export-untracked-modified-moved-and-deleted-files-from-a-git-repository-to-archive/</link>
        <pubDate>Sat, 12 Apr 2014 16:35:56 +0300</pubDate>
        
        <guid>https://manios.org/2014/04/12/export-untracked-modified-moved-and-deleted-files-from-a-git-repository-to-archive/</guid>
        <description>&lt;p&gt;Today I wanted to export to a .tar.gz archive all unstracked (new) , modified and deleted files from a Git repository. After some searching, I found &lt;a class=&#34;link&#34; href=&#34;http://stackoverflow.com/questions/855767/can-i-use-git-diff-on-untracked-files&#34;  target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;
    &gt;a StackOverflow post&lt;/a&gt; which helped a lot. So after you &lt;strong&gt;cd&lt;/strong&gt; inside your repository and you have two options:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;export-modified-moved-and-deleted-files&#34;&gt;Export modified moved and deleted files
&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;div class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;
&lt;table class=&#34;lntable&#34;&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class=&#34;lntd&#34;&gt;
&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt;1
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td class=&#34;lntd&#34;&gt;
&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-shell&#34; data-lang=&#34;shell&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;tar zvcf ~/new-files-cache.tar.gz &lt;span class=&#34;sb&#34;&gt;`&lt;/span&gt;git diff --name-only --diff-filter&lt;span class=&#34;o&#34;&gt;=&lt;/span&gt;ACMRT&lt;span class=&#34;sb&#34;&gt;`&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;h2 id=&#34;export-untracked-new-modified-and-deleted-files&#34;&gt;Export &lt;strong&gt;Untracked (new)&lt;/strong&gt;, modified and deleted files
&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;To achieve that I followed another custom route. If you find something smarter, please inform me!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;div class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;
&lt;table class=&#34;lntable&#34;&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class=&#34;lntd&#34;&gt;
&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;lnt&#34;&gt;1
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td class=&#34;lntd&#34;&gt;
&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-shell&#34; data-lang=&#34;shell&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;tar zvcf ~/new-files-cache.tar.gz &lt;span class=&#34;sb&#34;&gt;`&lt;/span&gt; git status --short &lt;span class=&#34;p&#34;&gt;|&lt;/span&gt; sed &lt;span class=&#34;s1&#34;&gt;&amp;#39;s/^ *[^ ]* \(.*\)/\1/g&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&#34;sb&#34;&gt;`&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;That&amp;rsquo;s it! Have fun with Git!&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
        </item>
        <item>
        <title>Windows 7 64bit ODBC Data sources</title>
        <link>https://manios.org/2012/09/26/windows-7-64bit-odbc-data-sources/</link>
        <pubDate>Wed, 26 Sep 2012 14:52:39 +0300</pubDate>
        
        <guid>https://manios.org/2012/09/26/windows-7-64bit-odbc-data-sources/</guid>
        <description>&lt;p&gt;Today I was trying to create and ODBC Data Source to a database using 32 bit database drivers. When I accessed ODBC Data Sources (32bit) from Control Panel, I could not create a data source using 32 bit drivers and I was facing two &lt;code&gt;Driver not found&lt;/code&gt; errors which can be seen in the following screenshots:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://manios.org/2012/09/26/windows-7-64bit-odbc-data-sources/dbdriverreinstall64bit.png&#34;
	width=&#34;410&#34;
	height=&#34;145&#34;
	srcset=&#34;https://manios.org/2012/09/26/windows-7-64bit-odbc-data-sources/dbdriverreinstall64bit_hu_91c93aee535c7db0.png 480w, https://manios.org/2012/09/26/windows-7-64bit-odbc-data-sources/dbdriverreinstall64bit_hu_63ef1bcc946e63af.png 1024w&#34;
	loading=&#34;lazy&#34;
	
		alt=&#34;odbc administrator error reinstall driver - Database Driver not found error&#34;
	
	
		class=&#34;gallery-image&#34; 
		data-flex-grow=&#34;282&#34;
		data-flex-basis=&#34;678px&#34;
	
&gt; &lt;img src=&#34;https://manios.org/2012/09/26/windows-7-64bit-odbc-data-sources/dbdrivernotfound64bit.png&#34;
	width=&#34;417&#34;
	height=&#34;165&#34;
	srcset=&#34;https://manios.org/2012/09/26/windows-7-64bit-odbc-data-sources/dbdrivernotfound64bit_hu_bc85cff7840731fb.png 480w, https://manios.org/2012/09/26/windows-7-64bit-odbc-data-sources/dbdrivernotfound64bit_hu_7d1d61c9ffb02de7.png 1024w&#34;
	loading=&#34;lazy&#34;
	
		alt=&#34;odbc architecture mismatch between driver and application error Driverâ€™s ConfigDSN, ConfigDriver, or ConfigTranslator failed error&#34;
	
	
		class=&#34;gallery-image&#34; 
		data-flex-grow=&#34;252&#34;
		data-flex-basis=&#34;606px&#34;
	
&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;After searching in the web and asking my colleagues I found that when you want to use Microsoft ODBC Administrator for:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;64bit database drivers you have to run the 64bit version which is located in:
&lt;code&gt;C:\Windows\System32\odbcad32.exe&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;32bit database drivers you have to run the 32bit version which is located in:
&lt;code&gt;C:\Windows\SysWOW64\odbcad32.exe&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Both windows look identical but the underlying implementation is different.&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
        </item>
        <item>
        <title>Copy/Paste source code from Eclipse to Microsoft Word</title>
        <link>https://manios.org/2012/03/08/copypaste-source-code-from-eclipse-to-microsoft-word/</link>
        <pubDate>Thu, 08 Mar 2012 09:53:02 +0200</pubDate>
        
        <guid>https://manios.org/2012/03/08/copypaste-source-code-from-eclipse-to-microsoft-word/</guid>
        <description>&lt;p&gt;Today I wanted to copy and paste a piece of code from Eclipse Indigo to Microsoft Word 2007 &lt;strong&gt;and keep the syntax highlighting&lt;/strong&gt;. In some cases it worked but in some other not.
After searching in the webI found that if the area you want to copy has folded code in it, the syntax highlight will not be preserved (picture 1)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://manios.org/2012/03/08/copypaste-source-code-from-eclipse-to-microsoft-word/codefoldeclipse.png&#34;
	width=&#34;408&#34;
	height=&#34;111&#34;
	srcset=&#34;https://manios.org/2012/03/08/copypaste-source-code-from-eclipse-to-microsoft-word/codefoldeclipse_hu_988f79f48cdd0dfb.png 480w, https://manios.org/2012/03/08/copypaste-source-code-from-eclipse-to-microsoft-word/codefoldeclipse_hu_626b16e8117820cb.png 1024w&#34;
	loading=&#34;lazy&#34;
	
		alt=&#34;code fold&#34;
	
	
		class=&#34;gallery-image&#34; 
		data-flex-grow=&#34;367&#34;
		data-flex-basis=&#34;882px&#34;
	
&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So before you start copying and pasting from Eclipse to Microsoft Word unfold any part of the code you want to copy (picture 2)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://manios.org/2012/03/08/copypaste-source-code-from-eclipse-to-microsoft-word/nofolding.png&#34;
	width=&#34;409&#34;
	height=&#34;254&#34;
	srcset=&#34;https://manios.org/2012/03/08/copypaste-source-code-from-eclipse-to-microsoft-word/nofolding_hu_ce378b5de8a9250d.png 480w, https://manios.org/2012/03/08/copypaste-source-code-from-eclipse-to-microsoft-word/nofolding_hu_de8266b1bc24958e.png 1024w&#34;
	loading=&#34;lazy&#34;
	
		alt=&#34;unfold Code in Eclipse&#34;
	
	
		class=&#34;gallery-image&#34; 
		data-flex-grow=&#34;161&#34;
		data-flex-basis=&#34;386px&#34;
	
&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
        </item>
        
